'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': 'Since you mentioned that you had your app "without source code", are you sure that app was using the [username/password flow](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/develop/msal-authentication-flows#usernamepassword-ropc) ([ROPC](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/develop/v2-oauth-ropc))?

I not as familiar with ADAL Java but just looking at where it [builds the acquire token call for the username/password flow](https://github.com/AzureAD/azure-activedirectory-library-for-java/blob/cf2fe74a35c0d7cc6cce24165bb9be47068b6bcb/src/main/java/com/microsoft/aad/adal4j/AuthenticationContext.java#L177) it doesn't seem like a redirect URI is used, nor can you send it [as a parameter](https://github.com/AzureAD/microsoft-authentication-library-for-java/blob/dev/src/main/java/com/microsoft/aad/msal4j/UserNamePasswordParameters.java) in MSAL Java's username/password flow.

Maybe the old app was actually using the [authorization code flow](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/develop/msal-authentication-flows#authorization-code)? Unlike the username/password flow where user credentials are either hardcoded or retrieved from users through your own login page, the auth code flow is meant for web applications which redirects users to another place to enter their credentials (for example https://login.microsoftonline.com/).

Have a look at [our web app sample](https://github.com/Azure-Samples/ms-identity-java-webapp/tree/master/msal-java-webapp-sample) and see if it better matches what the app that used ADAL did. In that sample, [here](https://github.com/Azure-Samples/ms-identity-java-webapp/blob/b37376b1fc481704b9b96b77170f01392f44bcaa/msal-java-webapp-sample/src/main/java/com/microsoft/azure/msalwebsample/AuthFilter.java#L40) is where it builds a redirect URI, and [here](https://github.com/Azure-Samples/ms-identity-java-webapp/blob/b37376b1fc481704b9b96b77170f01392f44bcaa/msal-java-webapp-sample/src/main/java/com/microsoft/azure/msalwebsample/AuthHelper.java#L177) is where it uses that redirect URI to get an auth code (that is later used to get the access token).

The only other place I can think of where a redirect URI would be used is an [interactive request where MSAL opens the operating system's default browser](https://github.com/AzureAD/microsoft-authentication-library-for-java/wiki/Acquiring-Token-Interactively), however I don't think there was an ADAL equivalent for that auth flow and it's a pretty niche option so I'd be surprised if the old ADAL app was using it.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure-Samples/ms-identity-java-desktop/issues/comments/1104485302/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': '@makushima Perhaps the redirect URI is being used as the authority in the client app? They are often the same or pretty similar, so the terminology is often used interchangeably.

So in the sample, the section where the client app is created is where the authority/redirect URI is used:
```
PublicClientApplication pca = PublicClientApplication.builder(clientId)
                .authority(authority)  //<--- right here
                .build();
```

This is configured in the `applications.properties` file with the `AUTHORITY` field. Normally username/password flow works just with the basic `https://login.microsoftonline.com/organizations/` we have in there already, but if your ADAL app was using a redirect URI in the username/password flow then that might be the equivalent in MSAL.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure-Samples/ms-identity-java-desktop/issues/comments/1101808833/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': "Hello @makushima : This sample is meant to demonstrate the calling pattern for the [username/password flow](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/develop/msal-authentication-flows#usernamepassword-ropc), and doesn't need a redirect URI to retrieve tokens.

However, while username/password flow is supported it isn't recommended for applications accessed by normal users (it's more meant for simple back-end/devops scenarios). Depending on your scenario, I'd recommend checking out some other samples:
- If your users are [federated](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/hybrid/whatis-fed), you can use the [integrated windows auth flow](https://github.com/Azure-Samples/ms-identity-msal-java-samples/tree/main/2.%20Client-Side%20Scenarios/Integrated-Windows-Auth-Flow) to sign in users and get tokens without them needing to provide their passwords
- If your users don't have access to a browser, [device code flow](https://github.com/Azure-Samples/ms-identity-msal-java-samples/tree/main/2.%20Client-Side%20Scenarios/Device-Code-Flow) will allow them to sign in on users using their phone or other device
- If you're developing a web application, we have tutorials showing how to sign in users and access Azure resources for both [Java servlet projects](https://github.com/Azure-Samples/ms-identity-msal-java-samples/tree/main/3.%20Java%20Servlet%20Web%20App%20Tutorial) and [projects using the Spring framework](https://github.com/Azure-Samples/ms-identity-msal-java-samples/tree/main/4.%20Spring%20Framework%20Web%20App%20Tutorial)", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure-Samples/ms-identity-java-desktop/issues/comments/1093269501/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'created_at': '2022-03-15T17:40:27Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-15T17:40:27Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': "@ramsay2021 Unfortunately IWA is probably the best fully non-interactive flow, but there are a couple other options:

- [Device code flow](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/develop/msal-authentication-flows#device-code)
  - If you're trying to avoid UI interaction because users may not be able to access a browser on the device the app is running on, then you could use the device code flow. Your users would be able to use another device (such as their phone) to enter their credentials
- [Client credentials flow](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/develop/msal-authentication-flows#client-credentials)
  - It shouldn't need any UI interaction from users, but isn't really meant for applications that are tailored to specific users. If your scenario allows you to sort users into groups and access resources based on those groups (rather than by specific user's credentials/permissions), you could use this flow
- [Username/password flow](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/develop/msal-authentication-flows#usernamepassword)
  - If you happen to have access to your user's usernames and passwords, then you can get tokens by handling them directly. This flow isn't  recommended though, as there is an obvious risk of exposing the credentials

And for any of the flows our library supports, you should be able to use a [silent token call](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/develop/scenario-desktop-acquire-token?tabs=java#recommended-pattern) to repeatedly refresh cached tokens, so users won't need to interact with a UI and provide their credentials every time they need to sign in.

As for WAM, we unfortunately don't support it yet but we've just begun working on it and plan to have the same level of support as .NET. However, we don't expect this to be ready for a couple of months.", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/AzureAD/microsoft-authentication-library-for-java/issues/comments/1068267311/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'created_at': '2022-03-14T19:29:34Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-14T19:29:34Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': "Hello @ramsay2021 : Is the user you're trying to sign in as part of your local Active Directory, or was it created just in Azure AD?

As you can see in the 'constraints' section of our [Integrated Windows Auth](https://github.com/AzureAD/microsoft-authentication-library-for-java/wiki/Integrated-Windows-Authentication) page, the IWA flow only works for [federated](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/hybrid/whatis-fed) users, which are users that have [a shared identity](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/hybrid/whatis-hybrid-identity) in both Azure AD and your on-premises Active Directory. A 'managed' user, as referenced in the error message, refers to a user created directly in Azure AD without Active Directory backing, and our library can't retrieve those Azure AD credentials so it can't get a token for a managed user.

In order to use IWA to get tokens for your users silently, you'll need to make those users federated users: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/hybrid/whatis-hybrid-identity", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/AzureAD/microsoft-authentication-library-for-java/issues/comments/1067205295/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'created_at': '2022-03-07T20:05:50Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-07T20:05:50Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': "Hello @maximemousserin : Sorry for the delayed response. We're currently reworking a lot of our old documentation, but haven't gotten to the cache persistence stuff yet so unfortunately I don't have any better docs to link.

Essentially, the doc you linked describes that in order to persist the cache, you need to implement your own `ITokenCacheAccessAspect`. That interface has two core methods where you can define how the library behaves when using the cache:

- beforeCacheAccess
  - Called right before the library accesses the cache. Here you can define how data is loaded into the cache, such as adding tokens, accounts, or an entire cache to the current in-memory cache
- afterCacheAccess
  - Called right after the library access the cache. Here you can define how cached data is persisted, such as updating a file with a new state of the cache 

You shouldn't need to worry about handling the tokens for specific accounts, the library should be able to retrieve the correct tokens for you (either because the cache contains only one account, or you add the account as one of the parameters of a silent token request). The `TokenCache` class attached to every `PublicClientApplication` and `ConfidentialClientApplication` can return a list of all accounts and all ID/access/refresh tokens, but if you want a specific entry you'd need to find it in that list.

Also, you can have a look at this repo that has some helper methods for persisting token caches securely: https://github.com/AzureAD/microsoft-authentication-extensions-for-java

It was originally made for some internal projects, but is publicly available on Maven and might have some features that can help your use case: https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/com.microsoft.azure/msal4j-persistence-extension", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/AzureAD/microsoft-authentication-library-for-java/issues/comments/1061083945/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'created_at': '2022-02-23T21:25:28Z', 'updated_at': '2022-02-23T21:25:28Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': "So, after asking around and finding some folks who know more about how these access tokens are made, it's my understanding that access tokens simply don't have signatures that can be validated using normal methods. In this case, the token service put a 'nonce' value in the header (which you can see in your token), and I think that is used in some way to encrypt or otherwise change the token signature in a way that MS Graph can verify, but you can't since you generally aren't expected to.

Basically, although access tokens look like a JWT and generally follows that standard format, some Microsoft resources may need non-standard things in access tokens which mess up this sort of validation. I believe ID tokens are more standard, so you should be able to verify them.

Check out this thread for some more details, it's from 2019 but I confirmed with some of the people in the thread that it's still more-or-less true today: https://github.com/AzureAD/azure-activedirectory-identitymodel-extensions-for-dotnet/issues/609#issuecomment-524434987", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/AzureAD/microsoft-authentication-library-for-java/issues/comments/1049230318/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

## Edit 

By adding 

```
requires jdk.httpserver; 
```
to my module-info.java I was able to get past the errors

Based on [this answer in SO](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/71095750/javafx-msal4j-noclassdeffounderror?noredirect=1#comment125677742_71095750) sounds like it could be fixed with a module-info.java file or at minimum adding the step of adding that dependency into the project's module-info.java

[MRE](https://github.com/Jeremy-Code-F/Msal4JMre) Works with no exceptions and by taking out 

```
module com.example.msal4jdemo {
    requires javafx.controls;
    requires javafx.fxml;
    requires jdk.httpserver; // <- This line
    requires msal4j;


    opens com.example.msal4jdemo to javafx.fxml;
    exports com.example.msal4jdemo;
}
```

It can reproduce the error.

## Edit 

By adding 

```
requires jdk.httpserver; 
```
to my module-info.java I was able to get past the errors

Based on [this answer in SO](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/71095750/javafx-msal4j-noclassdeffounderror?noredirect=1#comment125677742_71095750) sounds like it could be fixed with a module-info.java file or at minimum adding the step of adding that dependency into the project's module-info.java

[MRE](https://github.com/Jeremy-Code-F/Msal4JMre) Works with no exceptions and by taking out 

```
module com.example.msal4jdemo {
    requires javafx.controls;
    requires javafx.fxml;
    requires jdk.httpserver; // <- This line
    requires msal4j;


    opens com.example.msal4jdemo to javafx.fxml;
    exports com.example.msal4jdemo;
}
```

It can reproduce the error.

* Remove unneeded references and test for old Azure Germany cloud

* Moving tests to an existing file

* Adding copyright line

* Adding comments

* Bump version numbers for 1.11.1 release (#460)
